Compilation of issue faced in 6 years with Skoda Rapid 1.6 ambitious plus diesel

üéâWhy You Shouldn't buy Skoda Car?

Key Highlights of My Pathetic Skoda Car Experience over 6 years (2014 Oct to 2021 Jan):
Electronic Instrument Issue Indicators, Brake Failure while vehicle was running. Engine Stopped while Vehicle was running and Finally Fuel Injector Failures.

Its absolutely necessary to read Full Story below If You are or anyone in your circle have plans to purchase Skoda Car and do share this post!

I bought my first car Skoda Rapid Ambition+ Diesel from Vinayak Cars on October 2014 and Below are the Key Highlight of 6 years painful journey with ≈†KODA India TAFE Access ≈†KODA

Issue 1. Electronic Indicator Issue: For no reason multiple indicator like Glow plug, Brake fluid etc. used to show as red and I had to rush to workshop as suggested in their manual
that vehicle shouldn't be driven with any red light indicators. Solution Skoda used to offer was to update the Software and i have visited at least 6 times for the same issue.

Issue 2. Brake Failure Issue in 2017: I had big shock where my brake stopped working in running condition and I had to stop car using handbrake and then I again left the car to workshop
they did thorough analysis and said issue is fixed. It again failed in 2 months and I blasted Vinayak Skoda for being irresponsible in lying to me that the issue is fixed and after the second attempt also issue was not fixed. I had to seek my Friend's help Akhilesh who gave a solution to Skoda guys to try and after trying that fix brake issue got solved. Seriously this Service team couldn't fix Electronic Indicator and Brake issue.

3. Engine Cease in Apr 2018: I had got fresh service done and in 2 months my car stops in middle of city traffic in Koramangala. Nearest service station was TAFE Access ≈†KODA and here my more painful journey started with TAFE Access ≈†KODA and they analyzed that coolant kit is gone and told other few things and billed me 41000 rupees. Dealer gave me fake price quotation, & cheated more than 75000/-
Also not gave us the second key of my car.
Collected 1% TCS i.e. 12000/- as per government norms & didn‚Äôt deposited in government till date.
I am feeling completely cheated by Skoda and do not know what to do with my car.
So, request all those who plan to buy Skoda to reconsider their decision and ensure they have adequate reasons to buy.

Nice review. I would like to share my my experience with you guys as owning the colour (Carbon Steel) DSG Skoda Rapid 2017. The car is best handler in its segment. The colour looks beautiful i personally don't like the braking on automatic cars (this is a person to person view) . I've grown in love with this car have ridden it 10,000 Km in 3 months. Few problems i've faced if you sit up 4/5 people in car the car is sure to scrape on speed breakers . The mud flaps are very easy to break over our Indian roads. DRL cannot be switched off ( that can be irritating for some) . This car is absolutely worth the ‚Çπ. The ride might be too hard for some people's liking

textDisplay:
Hi DDS, I keep on watching your videos and find them very informative. I never owned a car, don't know how to drive, and don't even know much about cars. But now since family requirements are growing, I'm planning to buy one, and your channel has been a source of learning. My budget is 10L (I don't want to take loan), I want automatic/semi-automatic gear box (since that will be easy to learn), safety is the top priority. My daily run is not much, I work from home, so does my wife, but we like to go on drives over weekends, drive to nearby (100/150Km) destinations etc.
I zeroed down on Tata punch (5 star rating, great built quality, etc). Do you think, it is a good choice for me? Also, I know, you have suggested that ADVENTURE RHYTHM is the value of money option. But as a new driver, I feel having more features like (LED DRLs, rear wiper, defogger etc) will help me. So, I am considering CREATIVE variant as well. Please suggest, if my thinking is on right track.
textOriginal:

My daily run is not much, I work from home, so does my wife, but we like to go on drives over weekends, drive to nearby (100/150Km) destinations etc. 
I zeroed down on Tata punch (5 star rating, great built quality, etc). Do you think, it is a good choice for me? Also, I know, you have suggested that ADVENTURE RHYTHM is the value of money option. textDisplay:
Guys please check the dealer. If he is really trustworthy only then put your foot forward.
After doing so much research on which car we should finally buy, we opted for Skoda Rapid style automatic Petrol, and here are we today regretting for the same.
Think twice before you buy.
After sales service from Skoda is pathetic.
From day one there is some or the other problem but no one to rescue.
Dealer gave me fake price quotation, & cheated more than 75000/-
Also not gave us the second key of my car.
Collected 1% TCS i.e. 12000/- as per government norms & didn‚Äôt deposited in government till date.
I am feeling completely cheated by Skoda and do not know what to do with my car.
So, request all those who plan to buy Skoda to reconsider their decision and ensure they have adequate reasons to buy.

Edit. This car looked fantastic to me. And the one we called the Estelle as well. I would get one tomorrow if I could for the memories. Left hand drive or right hand drive, it doesn't matter. textDisplay: I have had this car for 2 years, the TS 1.2  SE model (petrol). The space inside including legroom is excellent. The fuel economy is much better than my previous car which was a Mark 2 Ford Focus. Road tax is ¬£30 a year. I really can't fault this car. I agree that you do feel a bump if you go over a pothole, that doesn't bother me..............I try never to go over potholes. I cannot agree with the 'disconcerting at motorway speeds comments' and would suspect this test car may have had an underinflated tyre or something because my car definitely does not give that feel at any speed on motorways. As for it not being exciting to drive, well as there's nowhere left in the UK where you can actually drive any car in an 'exciting' manner due to roadworks, potholes, speed traps and speed cameras, I don't think it's relevant whether it's exciting or not. I would definitely recommend this car as a good value for money purchase. If you are considering one, go for the SE model or above as it has built in Sat Nav and better spec than the basic models.

I need not pay single penny during the yearly service unless I go for extra services like wheel alignment, AC cleaning, etc. Rapid is one solid car. Other brands I feel it's all show and no go. Even with respect to looks of the car, I feel Rapid looks elegant and aged like fine wine. Comparing with other brands it's like German boy vs Korean/Japanese girl.
I agree with the point that service center should be available in your place because it gives a peace of mind that you can reach out if you face any problems.

textDisplay:
I have to disagree with you guys. First, this soft suspension you mentioned is really not bad at all. I find it to be very comfortable even. It smooths out light waves on the road very well. Sure, on some pot holes it can get a bit shaky but trust me, I would still rather sit in my Rapid than in a 2017 BMW 5 series I've rode in or even my parents' 2017 Octavia. Hard suspension makes it feel like a punch rather than a shaking experience which you get in the Rapid. It sure is preferable.
Second, I own the 1.0 TSI 95 hp engine and I can say that it's actually very good on the motorway. Sure, there are faster cars but what's to be expected nowadays where you find 200+ hp engines in family cars and V6 with 300 hp in a mini bus. One thing that is annoying is that quite often the engine seems to switch into some eco modes or whatever it is supposed to be but it reduces its power noticeably. It's not by much, it's still very quick and flexible but it needs a bit more time to get going. It never got me in trouble when overtaking for example or when waiting for too long when I don't have the right of way but decide to use a gap. Fully loaded with 5 people and full trunk - no problem. My car never failed me in terms of power.
Also, in terms of fuel cost and taxes, for Bulgaria it's an excellent car. My fuel consumption is around 6l/100km, lately I even got it to around 5. I'm driving mostly in the city and on the motoway every now and then. It's especially efficient on country roads. Not city, not motorway. Normal 2 lane road. My record on such a road is 3,9l/100km for a trip of 250km. My yearly tax is 24 Bulgarian Leva. It's nothing.
One more thing I forgot to mention - the vents that you said were so bad and slow... Well, if my windshield becomes "wet" from the inside, the vents clear it almost immediately. In cold winter mornings where I have ice on my windshield, I just turn on the vents towards it on full blast and in like max 5 minutes it's clear. If I'm in a rush, I just spray some wiper fluid and it melts.
So, dear readers - I recommend the Rapid. Buy it without hesitation.

textDisplay: I just booked the rapid rider after taking a test drive. I was indeed surprised with the engine. Was expecting it to be like the naturally aspirated 1.0L engine seen in the old polo, but this is nothing like it!. Its 1.0L turbo GDI, which makes it a whole new league. Its super refined and quiet, ull see the torque kicking in at 1700ish rpm, which is due to the turbo, and at higher rpm the engine makes a sweet note. Anyone interested in this, do take a test drive. I was planning on going for Dzire, but the drive dynamics of the rapid literally made me take pity on Dzire. Service interval of this is only at 15K kms, which is decent. Even though maintenance may cost more I am indeed going with this, coz I don't think I'm gonna part with this car soon.

textDisplay: Hello, I own a Skoda Rapid diesel manual variant. Its really fun to drive this machine. I bought the new model in January 2017. I have drove 35000 kms till now.  If I drive smooth I have measured an average of 24-25 kmpl. While driving rough its average comes around 16-17 and 12-14 if really rough. I had met minor accidents and except scratches nothing major appears on body. Even in traffic the major enemies of a car are 2 wheelers who hit side mirrors and drivers hit rear bumpers with their best efforts. Nothing major observed and bumper still fits on its place as it is. So overall happy with car performance, stability, build quality, drive and simplicity. Must go for it if you are not a fan of Japanese engineering.

textDisplay: I had skoda rapid diesel ambition plus 105bhp and 2014 model. I had it in manual transmission, believe me its one of the best cars in its segment in India. It depends upon how u drive and keep the car. For manual transmission and normal driving conditions with timely servicing, it gave me 25+ kmpl on higways and 19+ in city driving. I was pleased with the overall results of economy and other features inside the cabin as well. I wont say its the luxuriest of all but certainly its the best of all. For me the servicing was also reasonable no extra costs of any parts till its first 3 years of running. I would certainly recommend this car for those who dont do rash driving and like a simple and pleasurable experience from their cars.

textDisplay:
Happy and proud owner of ≈†koda Rapid 1.6 MPI Ambition. I agree with all the points mentioned except I get better mileage figures.

What I love?
1. A true entry luxury car on par with European design and feel.
2. Engine performance in terms of mileage.
3. Steering feedback.
4. Solid build which inspires big confidence.

What I don't like?
1. TSI would have been better than MPI
2. Interior materials could have been of better quality.
3. Optional airbags for passengers would have been beneficial.

On the whole I am very satisfied about the car and look forward to cover at least 200,000 km on the odometer :)

textDisplay:
Skoda cars are for those who like quality, safety and sturdiness...service costs are so much less now a days and it's only once a year unless 3 times for others.. I paid max 6500 per service max...this car when u sit inside then you know you are in a car which is strong and will keep you safe. Those who talk about mileage think why is it so? Why others have low weight? Could it be due to cheap and light materials?
Those who want to buy a car thinking about resale...well stick to cars built with 18mm sheets, they are cheap to buy, cheap to maintain, good resale and unless u land in an accident they will serve u well. For me a couple of lacs extra over a cars lifetime for multiple times more sturdiness, safety & reliability, and not to mention the luxury that comes with these German cars is worth it !!

Hi i am from Bangalore, Never ever buy any VW or VW group vehicles like skoda, audi, bentley etc
Ower of a topend skoda rapid diesel with DSG bought in Nov of 2014 with extended warrenty the car has run 63336 and car won't shift from 1st to 2nd gear jumps directly to 3rd and from 3rd directly to 5th car won't reverse, took it to skoda tafe access service centre near hosur they suspect a Mecatronic failure (DSG gear box failure) quoting 100000 claiming it depends on driving style a diesel car thats 4years old just out of extended warrenty has run 60k and has a sealed DSG with no driver involvement in gear shifts we had been loyal skoda customers ftom 2012 owned a fabia upgraded to rapid where planning for kodiaq now this issue we are at a fix totally confused and feeling cheated, outside India in china skoda is providing 10years warrenty on DSG units but why this attitude towards Indian consumers when VW knows they have problems with the DSG why sell it claiming the issues are all fixed, extremely dissapointed may soon sue them over this.
